A 28-year old man (names withheld) has been confirmed dead from Lassa fever in Umuahia, the Abia state capital, thus raising fears of possible outbreak of the disease in the state. Chief Egbulefu Eze, the permanent secretary, Ministry of Health, told newsmen in his office in the state capital that the man died at the Federal Medical Centre (FMC), Umuahia, on January 1. “I want to report about an outbreak of Lassa fever at Olokoro community in Umuahia South local government area and this is the fourth time we have had the outbreak for 20 years ago,” he said. Explaining that the result came after a thorough investigation of the report, he added that the ministry had always contained the outbreaks and was already on top of the situation again. The permanent secretary, who explained that every person that came in close contact with the victim have been identified and placed on surveillance, added that there was no cause for panic. Eze further said that officers of the Disease Surveillance of the ministry have held meetings with the state office of the World Health Organisation (WHO) to strategize on further action to take. Confirming the report, the medical director of the FMC, Dr Azubuike Onyebuchi said initially, that the patient was thought to be suffering from acute appendicitis and was rushed to theatre for surgery. He explained that when it was discovered that he had Lassa fever, the theatre was shut down and the entire personnel that came into contact with him were placed on 21 days surveillance. Meanwhile, the chairman of the Medical Advisory Council (CMAC), Dr. Ugochukwu Onyeonoro said that the FMC has been decontaminated, just as the CMAC alerted the ministry about the discovery immediately.